05698nam a22007215i 9780822383550DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20022002ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223835507 a10.1515/97808223835502doi  a(DE-B1597)554318  a(OCoLC)1226680185  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aB105.C473bC65 2002 7aPHI0040002bisacsh04a001221  aCC 7700qBVB2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/17689:00aComplexities :bSocial Studies of Knowledge Practices /cJohn Law, E. Roy Weintraub, Barbara Herrnstein Smith, Annemarie Mol. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2002] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (302 p.) :b4 b&w photos, 2 tables, 9 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aScience and Cultural Theory00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tComplexities: An Introduction -- tRomantic and Baroque Conceptions of Complex Wholes in the Sciences -- tWhich Road to Follow? The Moral Complexity of an ''Equipped'' Humanity -- tOn Space and Depth -- tOn Hidden Heterogeneities: Complexity, Formalism, and Aircraft Design -- tIn the Middle of the Network -- tWhen Elephants Stand for Competing Philosophies of Nature: Amboseli National Park, Kenya -- tWriting and (Re)writing Devices as Tools for Managing Complexity -- tCutting Surgeons, Walking Patients: Some Complexities Involved in Comparing -- tThe Disposal of Fear: Childhood, Trauma, and Complexity -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough much recent social science and humanities work has been a revolt against simplification, this volume explores the contrast between simplicity and complexity to reveal that this dichotomy, itself, is too simplistic. John Law and Annemarie Mol have gathered a distinguished panel of contributors to offer-particularly within the field of science studies-approaches to a theory of complexity, and at the same time a theoretical introduction to the topic. Indeed, they examine not only ways of relating to complexity but complexity in practice.Individual essays study complexity from a variety of perspectives, addressing market behavior, medical interventions, aeronautical design, the governing of supranational states, ecology, roadbuilding, meteorology, the science of complexity itself, and the psychology of childhood trauma. Other topics include complex wholes (holism) in the sciences, moral complexity in seemingly amoral endeavors, and issues relating to the protection of African elephants. With a focus on such concepts as multiplicity, partial connections, and ebbs and flows, the collection includes narratives from Kenya, Great Britain, Papua New Guinea, the Netherlands, France, and the meetings of the European Commission, written by anthropologists, economists, philosophers, psychologists, sociologists, and scholars of science, technology, and society.Contributors. Andrew Barry, Steven D. Brown, Michel Callon, Chunglin Kwa, John Law, Nick Lee, Annemarie Mol, Marilyn Strathern, Laurent Thévenot, Charis Thompson  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aComplexity (Philosophy). 0aKnowledge, Sociology of. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Epistemology.2bisacsh1 aBarry, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMol, Annemarie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThompson, Charis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKwa, Chunglin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaw, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThévenot, Laurent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaw, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStrathern, Marilyn, econtributor.